  "datePublished": "2025-12-26",
  "description": "The union of two sets is the set of everything that belongs to either one. If A={1,2,3}A = \\{1, 2, 3\\} and B={2,3,4,5}B = \\{2, 3, 4, 5\\}, then A∪B={1,2,3,4,5}A \\cup B = \\{1, 2, 3, 4, 5\\} — everything that is in AA, in BB, or in both. The elements that appear in both sets are not counted twice; they simply appear once in the union. Union is the \u0026ldquo;or\u0026rdquo; operation on sets: x∈A∪Bx \\in A \\cup B means x∈Ax \\in A or x∈Bx \\in B (or both).\n",
